USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only does the same text use the phrase “like in Iraq” several times, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for his own statement: “A New Way Forward.”
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences".
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only one possible and successful, so that today there is no talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, yet objectively he left his successor in a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but came up with nothing better, so he at least misled the general over 10,000 military.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders abide by the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is kept.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. After him will remain the patriarchal tribal relations.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relationships, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is “capable of action,” a minimal goal of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy is shattered by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to “soon return home” will perform some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the relationship between the security of Germany or Italy and the war with the Hindu Kush is.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions exert no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek the answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if it turns out to be a total failure.
