A management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies with respect to their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies for conquering markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have no relation to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
An employee demobilization can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved ... conduct themselves proactively and have a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would be to put employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that the American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuited to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any business management reasoning or practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can monitor, anticipate and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “in place”.
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
