The Dinosaur's Cradle
The Tawa trovae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: a two-meter-long, 1.50-meter-high animal that ran on its two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa trovae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation, and characteristics of early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we’ve found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of five specimens.
Finding Confirms Theories of Ancient Dinosaur History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not share such enthusiasm at all.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, about when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadrupedal sauropods known as "long-necked" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia a hervorb<0xC3><0xAD>.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa trovae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of air pockets, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air pockets, the birds’ breathing is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawae, the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air pockets, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa finds the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
The three cannot be descended from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to dominant Mesozoic land vertebrates remains an enigma.
While in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of modern crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct on the boundary from the Triassic to the Jurassic.
Successful stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact curbed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
