Emergency braking assistance is already mandatory
As happened with the ABS anti-lock brakes and will pass with the ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of absence is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to its way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions per range.
The emergency braking assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s step.
But it doesn’t always hold that pressure until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident had failed to step on the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance that the car uses to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided a year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In case it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
